BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) — Gov. Doug Burgum has picked a former newspaper publisher to serve as the next state tax commissioner.The Bismarck Tribune reported Tuesday that the governor named Public Service Commissioner Brian Kroshus to the post. Kroshus, a Republican, left his job as publisher of the Tribune in 2015 to mount an unsuccessful run for state auditor. Burgum appointed him to the PSC in 2017. He chaired the commission for two years beginning in 2019.Kroshus will replace outgoing Tax Commissioner Ryan Rauschenberger. He was jailed in November after he allegedly passed out drunk in a Bismarck hotel room that wasn’t his. A day  after the incident he announced he would resign effective Jan. 3.